The four pillars of OOP are fundamental to software design:

**1. Encapsulation** 🔒
Bundling data (properties) and methods that operate on that data within a single unit (class), while restricting direct access from outside.
```
class BankAccount {
  private balance = 0;
  public deposit(amount) { this.balance += amount; }
  public getBalance() { return this.balance; }
}
```

**2. Inheritance** 🧬
A mechanism where a child class inherits properties and methods from a parent class, promoting code reuse.
```
class Animal { speak() { } }
class Dog extends Animal { speak() { return 'Woof!'; } }
```

**3. Polymorphism** 🔄
The ability of objects to take many forms. The same method name can behave differently based on the object calling it.
- **Compile-time:** Method overloading
- **Runtime:** Method overriding

**4. Abstraction** 🎭
Hiding complex implementation details and exposing only the necessary interface to the user.
```
class EmailService {
  // User only calls send(), not the SMTP details
  send(to, subject, body) { ... }
}
```

**Interview Tip:** Be ready to give real-world analogies (e.g., a car steering wheel is abstraction — you don't need to know how the engine works).

**Class vs Object — A Clear Comparison:**

| Feature | Class | Object |
|---------|-------|--------|
| Definition | A blueprint/template | An instance of a class |
| Memory | No memory allocated | Memory allocated on creation |
| Creation | Defined using `class` keyword | Created using `new` keyword |
| Count | Defined once | Multiple objects from same class |

**Real-World Analogy:**
• **Class** = Architectural blueprint of a house
• **Object** = The actual house built from that blueprint

**Code Example:**
```javascript
// Class (blueprint)
class Car {
  constructor(brand, model) {
    this.brand = brand;
    this.model = model;
  }
  drive() { return `${this.brand} ${this.model} is driving!`; }
}

// Objects (instances)
const car1 = new Car('Toyota', 'Camry');
const car2 = new Car('Honda', 'Civic');
```

**Key Point:** A class defines the structure and behavior; an object is a concrete entity with actual values.

Promises and async/await handle asynchronous operations in JavaScript:

**Callback Hell (The Problem):**
```javascript
getUser(id, (user) => {
  getOrders(user, (orders) => {
    getDetails(orders[0], (details) => {
      // Deeply nested = hard to read/maintain
    });
  });
});
```

**Promise (The Solution):**
A Promise represents a value that may be available in the future.
```javascript
const promise = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
  const data = fetchData();
  data ? resolve(data) : reject('Error!');
});

promise
  .then(data => console.log(data))
  .catch(err => console.error(err))
  .finally(() => console.log('Done'));
```

**async/await (The Cleaner Syntax):**
```javascript
async function getUserData(id) {
  try {
    const user = await getUser(id);
    const orders = await getOrders(user);
    return orders;
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Failed:', error);
  }
}
```

**Promise States:**
• ⏳ Pending → Initial state
• ✅ Fulfilled → Operation succeeded
• ❌ Rejected → Operation failed

**Pro Tip:** Use `Promise.all()` for parallel execution, `Promise.allSettled()` when you need all results regardless of failures.

**React** is a JavaScript library for building user interfaces:

**Core Concepts:**

**1. Components:** Reusable UI building blocks
```jsx
function Greeting({ name }) {
  return <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>;
}
```

**2. JSX:** HTML-like syntax in JavaScript
```jsx
const element = <div className="card">{user.name}</div>;
```

**3. Virtual DOM:** React creates a lightweight copy of the real DOM
• When state changes → new Virtual DOM is created
• React diffs old vs new Virtual DOM (Reconciliation)
• Only changed elements are updated in the real DOM
• Result: Faster, more efficient UI updates

**4. Hooks (React 16.8+):**
```jsx
function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  useEffect(() => {
    document.title = `Count: ${count}`;
  }, [count]);

  return <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>{count}</button>;
}
```

**Key Hooks:**
• `useState` — Manage component state
• `useEffect` — Side effects (API calls, subscriptions)
• `useContext` — Share data without prop drilling
• `useRef` — Access DOM elements directly
• `useMemo` / `useCallback` — Performance optimization

**Interview Tip:** Understand the component lifecycle and be able to explain how React optimizes rendering.

**Design Patterns** are reusable solutions to common software design problems:

**Creational Patterns** (Object Creation)
1. **Singleton:** Only one instance of a class exists
```javascript
class Database {
  static instance;
  static getInstance() {
    if (!Database.instance) Database.instance = new Database();
    return Database.instance;
  }
}
```

2. **Factory:** Creates objects without specifying exact class
```javascript
class VehicleFactory {
  create(type) {
    if (type === 'car') return new Car();
    if (type === 'truck') return new Truck();
  }
}
```

**Structural Patterns** (Object Composition)
3. **Adapter:** Makes incompatible interfaces work together
4. **Decorator:** Adds behavior to objects dynamically

**Behavioral Patterns** (Object Communication)
5. **Observer:** When one object changes, all dependents are notified
```javascript
eventEmitter.on('userCreated', sendWelcomeEmail);
eventEmitter.on('userCreated', initializeProfile);
eventEmitter.emit('userCreated', userData);
```

6. **Strategy:** Defines a family of algorithms, makes them interchangeable

**MVC Pattern:**
• **Model:** Data and business logic
• **View:** UI/presentation
• **Controller:** Handles input, updates model/view

**Interview Tip:** Don't just memorize patterns — explain when and why you'd use each one with a real-world scenario.
